# Fixture (iii): self-supporting cycle (drains to empty) vs firewalled
# cycle (refuses the cascade), plan.md :331-353 trace, doubled onto two
# disjoint node pairs {1,2} and {3,4} sharing one program.
#
# Batch 1: edges for both cycles (1<->2 and 3<->4), never retracted.
# Batch 2: base(1) only (drain scenario) AND base(3)+base(4) (firewall
#   scenario) seeded together.
# Batch 3: retract base(1) AND base(3) in the SAME batch (one epoch
#   exercises both the drain arm and the firewall-refusal arm
#   simultaneously, on independent SCCs, so a wrong REDERIVE/firewall
#   implementation that corrupts cross-row bookkeeping shows up in BOTH
#   halves of one oracle run).
#
# Expected end state: p_out = {3, 4} only. {1,2} fully drains (no
# firewall: base(1) was p(1)/p(2)'s only support). {3,4} survives fully:
# base(4) firewalls p(4), so the p(3)<-p(4),edge(4,3) instance keeps
# reviving p(3) even after base(3) is gone.
batch
+ edge 1 2
+ edge 2 1
+ edge 3 4
+ edge 4 3
end

batch
+ base 1
+ base 3
+ base 4
end

batch
- base 1
- base 3
end
